🏗 Section 5: Managing Requirements & Their Evolution

Role & Purpose in the Manual
	•	This is one of the core pillars of the manual: correct handling of requirements is foundational to controlling cost, scope, quality, and risk.
	•	It converts the abstract notions of “vague requirements” and “requirement drift” into practical governance, tooling, and behavior strategies.
	•	It bridges business intent → delivery unit (Feature, Epic, Story) → testability → change control.
	•	It also anchors the manual’s “protection logic”: if you master this section, many other problems (defects, rework, escalation) become smaller.

⸻

🎯 Promise of Section 5 (What Readers Will Gain)

By the end of Section 5, the reader will:
	•	Hold a clear taxonomy of Requirement → Feature → Epic → Story, and know who is responsible for what decomposition.
	•	Be able to specify “minimally acceptable requirements” (MAR) that are just sufficient for estimation, risk assessment, and design.
	•	Know how to gate requirements via Ready-for-Planning (RfP) maturity criteria — and enforce them in Jira.
	•	Recognize bad / ambiguous acceptance criteria, “smells,” and how to coach customers to refine them.
	•	Understand how requirements evolve (discovery, clarification, emergence) and how to treat each form.
	•	Be equipped to integrate external dependencies and integration contracts into requirement governance.
	•	Map requirements into dashboards and alerting (labels, statuses) to continuously monitor maturity, volatility, and risk.
	•	Be ready to engage in commercial conversations about cost of change and funding origin tied to requirement evolution.

