🧱 Shared Understanding: Core Content Elements & Concepts

Here are the major subtopics that must be in Section 5, plus a brief sketch of what needs to be covered under each, and where we embed the wisdom / coaching tone.

| Subsection                                      | What Must Be Explained / Delivered                                                                                                                                         | Wisdom / Coaching Anchor                                                                                                 |
|-------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| 5.1 Requirement Taxonomy & Ownership            | Define Requirement, Feature, Epic, Story; clarify responsibilities (Customer Team owns requirement, Delivery Team owns feature decomposition)                               | Why This Matters: mixing these terms is one of the biggest early confusion sources                                       |
| 5.2 Minimally Acceptable Requirements (MAR)     | What minimum elements a requirement must have (intent, boundaries, dependencies, constraints, initial acceptance criteria) before you can meaningfully estimate, architect, or decompose | Pro Tip: If you can’t write a test for it, it isn’t minimally acceptable                                                 |
| 5.3 Ready-for-Planning (RfP) Gate               | The maturity gate: conditions/criteria a requirement must satisfy before being allowed into sprint planning / estimation (all AC written, dependencies mapped, impacts assessed) | VP Insight: The number of “incomplete” RfP items is a leading indicator of planning risk                                |
| 5.4 Acceptance Criteria: Smells & Maturity      | What good ACs look like (testable, observable, data thresholds, deterministic) vs bad ones (vague, ambiguous, UI only, “as desired”)                                       | From the Field: “We once accepted a story because user said ‘works as expected’ — months later we discovered 3 scenarios that failed.” |
| 5.5 Requirement Evolution (Discovery / Clarification / Emergence) | Categorize change types, show how each should be handled differently (some are design discoveries, some new business input)                                                 | Caution: Lumping all changes into “scope creep” kills judgment                                                          |
| 5.6 Jira Practices for Requirement Control      | Labels, statuses, custom fields, automations, blockers, rule enforcement — how to codify maturity and evolution visibility in Jira                                         | Pro Tip: Use rfp-yes label, ac-missing, integration-risk flags to surface risk trends                                    |
| 5.7 Feature → Epic → Story Hierarchy & Decomposition | How to break down a requirement into a feature, then epics & stories, while maintaining traceability and ability to re-estimate                                            | Why This Matters: Estimating at Feature level gives negotiation anchor; re-estimation during decomposition must be controlled |
| 5.8 External Integrations & Dependencies        | How to treat interfaces, external APIs, SLAs, contracts, data exchange as first-class requirement elements                                                                 | VP Insight: Integrations are often the silent killers of deadlines                                                       |
| 5.9 Commercial Implications of Requirement Evolution | How changes map to cost/effort deltas, who funds them, when a change becomes a commercial negotiation                                                                      | From the Field: “We delivered the change gratis once — next time the customer assumed we’d always absorb.”               |
| 5.10 Dashboards & Alerts for Requirements       | Define metrics (e.g. % RfP, volatility, AC missing, dependency risk), alert thresholds, audience, escalation flows                                                         | Caution: Too many metrics kill signal — choose 8–12 focus ones per governance tier                                      |


